# Fluff Date: 2026-02-14 18:58:16
overview:<p>The Hermes III designation originally applied to the Draconis Combine's HER-4K variant of the Hermes II, but Luthien Armor Works' extensive post-Jihad upgrades have effectively created a new chassis bearing the same name. Built from salvaged HER-4K frames recovered from militias and scrapyards across the Combine, these modernized 'Mechs incorporate advanced technology that transforms the aging scouts into capable contemporary reconnaissance platforms.</p><p>Luthien Armor Works' involvement reflects the DCMS's urgent need to reconstitute its reconnaissance forces following the devastating losses of the Jihad. Rather than waiting for new construction, LAW's engineers developed comprehensive refit packages that could rapidly return damaged Hermes III frames to frontline service while dramatically improving their combat capabilities.</p>

capabilities:<p>The upgraded Hermes III retains the original's role as a heavy scout and skirmisher while significantly enhancing its combat potential. The refitted snub-nose PPCs provide effective firepower within 270 meters, offering pilots a measure of parity against contemporary medium 'Mechs without the range disadvantages of the original's large lasers. The sacrifice of the traditional flamer for an additional hand actuator improves the 'Mech's ability to manipulate objects during extended operations, a practical consideration for reconnaissance units operating far from supply lines.</p><p>Advanced electronics distinguish the modernized Hermes III from its predecessor. The proven Irian E.A.R. communications system receives upgrades including Guardian ECM integration and C3 slave capability, allowing the 'Mech to coordinate with Combine tactical networks while providing electronic countermeasures protection. The Cat's Eyes targeting computer enhances accuracy, partially compensating for the snub-nose PPCs' reduced effective range compared to standard particle cannons.</p><p>The chassis itself receives attention, with an Irian-Ost-LAW hybrid frame incorporating improvements developed through the partnership between the original manufacturer and its Combine counterpart. A GM 240 XL engine maintains the design's mobility while Samarkand Royal Heavy ferro-fibrous armor provides improved protection without excessive weight penalties.</p>

deployment:<p>The HER-6K represents Luthien Armor Works' comprehensive modernization of salvaged Hermes III frames recovered following the Jihad. Twin Lord's Light 5 snub-nose PPCs replace the original large lasers, providing effective medium-range firepower with improved damage potential at the cost of maximum engagement distance. The addition of a second hand actuator (replacing the original flamer) improves the 'Mech's utility during extended reconnaissance operations where object manipulation may prove necessary. Advanced electronics including Guardian ECM, C3 slave integration, and an upgraded targeting computer transform the aging scout into a capable network-enabled reconnaissance platform.</p>

history:<p>The original Hermes III emerged during the First Succession War when Ostmann Industries' Kuritan branch recognized the potential in Hermes II chassis imported under the Concord of Kapteyn. Their engineers transformed these Free Worlds League scouts into energy-focused strikers that eliminated ammunition dependency, creating a variant that proved popular enough to receive its own designation despite being built on the same forty-ton frame.</p><p>The Jihad's devastation of DCMS reconnaissance forces created urgent demand for capable scout platforms. Rather than waiting for new construction to fill the gap, Luthien Armor Works recovered damaged and abandoned HER-4K frames from across the Combine, developing comprehensive upgrade packages that could rapidly return these veterans to service. The New Samarkand Refit Facility became the primary center for this work, processing salvaged chassis and upgrading them to contemporary standards.</p><p>The upgraded Hermes III received its first combat test on Mualang in 3084 during a Ghost Bear incursion. Elements of the First Sword of Light's Third Battalion deployed several HER-6Ks on a flanking maneuver that surprised the Ninth Provisional Garrison Cluster, demonstrating the modernized design's reconnaissance and fire support capabilities. The engagement marked the end of serious Ghost Bear offensive operations on the world.</p><p>Subsequent deployments during the Second Combine-Dominion War further validated the design. At Trondheim in 3100, Hermes IIIs from the Eleventh Ghost were among the first 'Mechs to reach the ground during heavily contested combat drops, using their C3 integration to direct fire support while still descending. Luthien Armor Works continues developing new variants, with the HER-7K representing their latest effort to create the definitive version of this venerable chassis.</p>

